00:47:11.219 --> 00:47:13.760
AUDIENCE: I was wondering if
you think that there's something

00:47:13.760 --> 00:47:16.820
fundamental to human dignity,
human flourishing that's

00:47:16.820 --> 00:47:19.050
tied up with human labor.

00:47:19.050 --> 00:47:21.860
And if so, what that
means for us in an economy

00:47:21.860 --> 00:47:23.840
that's more
productive than ever,

00:47:23.840 --> 00:47:26.180
but in which human labor is
an increasingly diminishing

00:47:26.180 --> 00:47:26.680
component.

00:47:26.680 --> 00:47:27.513
ARTHUR BROOKS: Yeah.

00:47:27.513 --> 00:47:28.850
What a wonderful question.

00:47:28.850 --> 00:47:32.900
What is the inherency of dignity
that comes from human labor?

00:47:32.900 --> 00:47:35.780
I mean, there's really a
lot of philosophy on this.

00:47:35.780 --> 00:47:39.680
I mean, the idea of
sanctified ordinary work

00:47:39.680 --> 00:47:45.260
is a very common theme for
philosophers and theologians.

00:47:45.260 --> 00:47:48.250
And what many people
have written about this,

00:47:48.250 --> 00:47:50.510
just throughout the
ages, is that when

00:47:50.510 --> 00:47:52.950
people have a sense of
their own self-worth,

00:47:52.950 --> 00:47:55.560
it comes from
meaning and purpose.

00:47:55.560 --> 00:47:57.290
Meaning and purpose
only comes when

00:47:57.290 --> 00:48:00.160
you are serving others as
opposed to being served.

00:48:00.160 --> 00:48:01.850
This Is the paradox of it.

00:48:01.850 --> 00:48:03.814
When you're feeling
lousy about your life,

00:48:03.814 --> 00:48:05.480
you want other people
to serve you more.

00:48:05.480 --> 00:48:07.190
You want to stop feeling lousy?

00:48:07.190 --> 00:48:08.870
Go serve other people more.

00:48:08.870 --> 00:48:11.840
That paradoxical kind
of turning of the tables

00:48:11.840 --> 00:48:14.120
actually is one of the
great secrets to happiness.

00:48:14.120 --> 00:48:16.370
How can you do that
on a systematic basis,

00:48:16.370 --> 00:48:19.460
is by seeing your work
as service to others

00:48:19.460 --> 00:48:23.040
and making your work
into service to others.

00:48:23.040 --> 00:48:25.110
That's how no matter
what you're doing--

00:48:25.110 --> 00:48:27.890
whether you're coding or
you're building a wall

00:48:27.890 --> 00:48:30.140
or you're running a think tank--

00:48:30.140 --> 00:48:33.050
you can get greater joy from
it by remembering the people

00:48:33.050 --> 00:48:35.255
that you are trying
to serve, whether it's

00:48:35.255 --> 00:48:37.550
your coworkers or your clients.

00:48:37.550 --> 00:48:39.020
That's really hugely important.

00:48:39.020 --> 00:48:41.990
And this is a robust social
psychological finding

00:48:41.990 --> 00:48:45.530
and a theological finding and a
philosophical finding as well.

00:48:45.530 --> 00:48:49.070
Work brings happiness as long
as it is tied to purpose.

00:48:49.070 --> 00:48:51.680
And purpose comes from
serving other people.

00:48:51.680 --> 00:48:56.630
That's your job is to figure out
how to serve other people more.

00:48:56.630 --> 00:48:59.757
So what does it mean
when people work less?

00:48:59.757 --> 00:49:01.340
Let's not talk about
just service jobs

00:49:01.340 --> 00:49:03.980
where people have less
robust human labor

00:49:03.980 --> 00:49:06.350
or where people are even
cutting down on hours.

00:49:06.350 --> 00:49:08.840
Let's talk about an economy
where fewer and fewer people

00:49:08.840 --> 00:49:10.780
are needed in the workforce.

00:49:10.780 --> 00:49:13.310
You've created almost
perfect storm, a formula

00:49:13.310 --> 00:49:14.704
for unhappiness in doing that.

00:49:14.704 --> 00:49:17.120
So this is connected to what
I've been talking about here,

00:49:17.120 --> 00:49:17.620
right?

00:49:17.620 --> 00:49:20.510
We basically say--
anytime you say look,

00:49:20.510 --> 00:49:23.210
I don't think people should
have to take dead-end jobs,

00:49:23.210 --> 00:49:24.740
you basically said
you're not going

00:49:24.740 --> 00:49:27.999
to get dignity from work
because I've defined dignity out

00:49:27.999 --> 00:49:28.540
of your work.

00:49:28.540 --> 00:49:30.980
What an arrogant,
terrible thing to say.

00:49:30.980 --> 00:49:33.230
Who treats their brothers
and sisters that way?

00:49:33.230 --> 00:49:34.970
Everybody should
be able to work.

00:49:34.970 --> 00:49:36.560
Everybody should
have dignified work

00:49:36.560 --> 00:49:38.330
and get dignity from their work.

00:49:38.330 --> 00:49:39.680
No such thing as a dead-end job.

00:49:39.680 --> 00:49:40.910
That's critical.

00:49:40.910 --> 00:49:44.150
But what we're basically doing
in our economy, of course,

00:49:44.150 --> 00:49:45.740
is loading more
and more and more

00:49:45.740 --> 00:49:48.630
of the value on the
workforce onto you

00:49:48.630 --> 00:49:50.399
and onto me, the
people who are trying

00:49:50.399 --> 00:49:52.440
to get more and more and
more and more productive

00:49:52.440 --> 00:49:55.220
in the top 10% of the
income distribution.

00:49:55.220 --> 00:49:57.720
That's what we're actually
trying to do, in which case,

00:49:57.720 --> 00:49:59.450
we're basically saying
these things have

00:49:59.450 --> 00:50:01.560
more dignity than other people.

00:50:01.560 --> 00:50:03.080
What we should be
thinking about is

00:50:03.080 --> 00:50:06.620
finding ways for other
people to earn their way

00:50:06.620 --> 00:50:10.072
and not just in public policy,
in private industry as well.

00:50:10.072 --> 00:50:11.780
And in doing that,
we'll have the formula

00:50:11.780 --> 00:50:14.570
for passing on the blessings
that we take for granted.

00:50:14.570 --> 00:50:17.540
For you, for me, the
one thing for you

00:50:17.540 --> 00:50:19.640
to take away from
what I just said

00:50:19.640 --> 00:50:22.580
is that meaning comes from work
when work provides service.

00:50:22.580 --> 00:50:24.420
And service is all
about other people.

00:50:24.420 --> 00:50:29.186
How am I serving my fellow
men and women more today?

00:50:29.186 --> 00:50:30.560
I'm going to find
a way to do it.

00:50:30.560 --> 00:50:32.240
On your way to work
in the mornings,

00:50:32.240 --> 00:50:34.460
say I'm going to
serve more today.

00:50:34.460 --> 00:50:36.920
I'm going to find a
better way to serve today.

00:50:36.920 --> 00:50:39.937
And you go home happier with
a better appetite for dinner.

00:50:39.937 --> 00:50:41.520
Thank you for that
wonderful question.

00:50:41.520 --> 00:50:43.130
Yeah.

00:50:43.130 --> 00:50:45.260
AUDIENCE: How do you
incentivize the private sector

00:50:45.260 --> 00:50:50.450
to need the poor, especially
if it's less financially viable

00:50:50.450 --> 00:50:52.917
than say serving the top 10%?

00:50:52.917 --> 00:50:53.750
ARTHUR BROOKS: Yeah.

00:50:53.750 --> 00:50:57.080
I'm asking the private sector to
be more creative in doing that,

00:50:57.080 --> 00:50:58.730
because I think that
we're passing up

00:50:58.730 --> 00:51:00.020
all sorts of opportunities.

00:51:00.020 --> 00:51:04.010
And here's how I'd like to
ask you to think about it.

00:51:04.010 --> 00:51:08.210
As an historic matter, every
prosperous and successful

00:51:08.210 --> 00:51:12.470
society has made a major
inflection as prosperity

00:51:12.470 --> 00:51:16.770
on the basis of energy and
of an energy source, right?

00:51:16.770 --> 00:51:19.670
And sometimes it's
like finding oil.

00:51:19.670 --> 00:51:24.560
But usually energy sources are
tied up in human ingenuity.

00:51:24.560 --> 00:51:27.760
So the United States had a
major inflection of prosperity,

00:51:27.760 --> 00:51:32.300
of productivity when we figured
out that universal education is

00:51:32.300 --> 00:51:33.290
a really good thing.

00:51:33.290 --> 00:51:35.540
Universal public education
is a great thing.

00:51:35.540 --> 00:51:37.130
It's a huge public good.

00:51:37.130 --> 00:51:39.890
It unlocked massive
amounts of human energy

00:51:39.890 --> 00:51:42.530
and turn America into
a really great country.

00:51:42.530 --> 00:51:44.390
It wasn't that long
ago, by the way.

00:51:44.390 --> 00:51:47.150
It was like in the late
part of the 19th century was

00:51:47.150 --> 00:51:48.620
when this started to happen.

00:51:48.620 --> 00:51:50.330
It went along with
Industrial Revolution.

00:51:50.330 --> 00:51:52.490
But it unlocked the
human capital revolution

00:51:52.490 --> 00:51:53.870
in this country.

00:51:53.870 --> 00:51:56.600
Energy sources are
a really big deal.

00:51:56.600 --> 00:51:58.910
What we need to do to
be more creative about,

00:51:58.910 --> 00:52:02.690
in the idea of part of the
private sector in particular--

00:52:02.690 --> 00:52:04.530
we can talk about
manufacturing if you want.

00:52:04.530 --> 00:52:05.930
But basically look,
this is Google.

00:52:05.930 --> 00:52:07.310
This is the idea
part of the world.

00:52:07.310 --> 00:52:09.435
And I'm in the American
Enterprise Institute, which

00:52:09.435 --> 00:52:11.400
is an idea factory as well--

00:52:11.400 --> 00:52:14.670
is finding better ways
to unlock the next wave

00:52:14.670 --> 00:52:16.440
of human potential.

00:52:16.440 --> 00:52:18.810
The most productive
areas of human potential

00:52:18.810 --> 00:52:21.810
are going to be where it's
currently lying fallow,

00:52:21.810 --> 00:52:25.530
not where it's already at its
highest degree of utilization,

00:52:25.530 --> 00:52:26.400
right?

00:52:26.400 --> 00:52:28.800
You've all heard the
old axiom that if you

00:52:28.800 --> 00:52:31.500
want to get something
done, go to a busy person.

00:52:31.500 --> 00:52:33.450
That is true as far as it goes.

00:52:33.450 --> 00:52:34.892
But if you want
an army of people

00:52:34.892 --> 00:52:36.350
who are going to
do new things, you

00:52:36.350 --> 00:52:38.910
have to find people
who have free time.

00:52:38.910 --> 00:52:43.200
And if you want to find ways to
radically inflect productivity

00:52:43.200 --> 00:52:45.360
in this country, you
have to find the places

00:52:45.360 --> 00:52:47.310
where we're simply
not asking people

00:52:47.310 --> 00:52:49.110
to put their oar
in the water enough

00:52:49.110 --> 00:52:51.480
and find ways to help
them get that done.

00:52:51.480 --> 00:52:54.570
What is Google doing to
enhance the productivity

00:52:54.570 --> 00:52:58.080
and the productive capacity
of people who are currently

00:52:58.080 --> 00:53:01.000
behind the curtain
of how technology

00:53:01.000 --> 00:53:04.830
can enhance effectively
their intelligence

00:53:04.830 --> 00:53:05.970
and their productivity?

00:53:05.970 --> 00:53:08.205
I mean, Google has made
me-- it's unbelievable

00:53:08.205 --> 00:53:10.140
what this company has
done for me, by the way.

00:53:10.140 --> 00:53:11.348
I'll tell you what it's done.

00:53:11.348 --> 00:53:14.940
I mean, it's given me the
capacity at my fingertips,

00:53:14.940 --> 00:53:17.400
with just me and devices.

00:53:17.400 --> 00:53:20.710
It's given me the
imagination, creativity,

00:53:20.710 --> 00:53:23.460
and the effective intelligence
far beyond the dreams

00:53:23.460 --> 00:53:25.340
of Leonardo da Vinci.

00:53:25.340 --> 00:53:27.960
That's what it's done in just
the last few years, right?

00:53:27.960 --> 00:53:31.350
But why is it that the people
we're adding to in this way

00:53:31.350 --> 00:53:33.630
are the people who
needed it the least?

00:53:33.630 --> 00:53:36.660
And why do we keep finding
ways to make people at the top

00:53:36.660 --> 00:53:40.006
more productive, more
creative, more prosperous?

00:53:40.006 --> 00:53:41.880
Why are we not looking
for people who are not

00:53:41.880 --> 00:53:42.921
at that particular place?

00:53:42.921 --> 00:53:45.074
That's my challenge
to you, my friends.

00:53:45.074 --> 00:53:46.740
That's what we should
be thinking about,

00:53:46.740 --> 00:53:50.700
not just as social justice
warriors, but as people

00:53:50.700 --> 00:53:54.480
who are trying to be
economically savvy, who

00:53:54.480 --> 00:53:58.140
are looking for the next great
post-industrial revolution.

00:53:58.140 --> 00:54:00.290
That's the answer that
we need to come up with.

00:54:00.290 --> 00:54:04.430
And that's the answer we need
to come up with together.

